    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-05T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-05T09:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.24/1583: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-05T23:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 5, 1941—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 5—10:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1400. Commercial Attaché’s<note n="79" xml:id="d299fn1">Frank S. Williams.</note>
                    colleague at the Netherlands Legation reported following statements made by
                    official of the commercial section of the Foreign Office. Shortage of crude
                    rubber in Japan becoming increasingly more acute since hopes for adequate
                    supplies from Indochina, Thailand unrealized, therefore would be vital [to] look
                    to Netherlands East Indies for further supplies. Official declared rubber stocks
                    in the United States now over 800,000 tons<note n="80" xml:id="d299fn2">In
                        telegram No. 585, September 11, 6 p.m., the Ambassador in Japan was informed
                        that the total stock of rubber in the United States as of July 31 was
                        395,216 tons and that it was increasing at the rate of about 50,000 tons a
                        month.</note> which amount, he pointed out, should be conformably adequate
                    for America’s war efforts. Dutch colleague reported saying in response that the
                    position of his Government remains unchanged and that no raw materials which
                    might eventually be used against the Netherlands and her allies including Soviet
                    Russia can be allowed exportation to Japan from the Indies. Dutch colleague
                    further reported that four Japanese tankers which have been in Netherland Indian
                    waters since the freezing order was enforced are still waiting for oil
                    cargoes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
